<subsection xml:id="subsec-recurring-decimals">
    <title>Recurring decimals</title>
    <p>
        <term>A recurring number</term>, also known as a repeating decimal, is a decimal number 
        in which a specific digit or group of digits after the decimal point repeats without ending.
    </p>
    <p>
        In recurring decimals, <alert>dot notation</alert> is used to indicate repeating digits.
        A dot placed above a specific digit or sequence of digits shows which part repeats. 
        For instance, <m>0.5\dot{7}</m> represents <m>0.577777...</m>, and <m>0.\dot{2}\dot{7}</m> represents <m>0.272727...</m>
    </p>
